ngland":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rethel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Ithell</i> ‘son of <i>Ithel</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘bountiful lord’. This name was adopted in Wales and elsewhere as a name for a chapel, as it is a homograph of a Biblical placename meaning ‘house of God’ in Hebrew (Genesis 12, 13, 28, and elsewhere in the Bible).","German: habitational name from Bethel in Westphalia."],"variants":[{"name":"Bithell","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Bethel  ."]},{"name":"Ethel","meanings":["(2007: 236; 2010: NA)","Welsh: from the personal name <i>Ithell</i>, Middle Welsh <i>Ithael</i>. See   Bethel  ."]},{"name":"Bethea","meanings":["Possibly an altered form of Welsh   Bethel  .","History: The name was brought to VA by John Bethea (known as ‘English John’) (1684– after 1750), who settled in Nansemond, VA."]},{"name":"Bethell","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Bethel  ."]}]},{"name":"Clemence","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval French and English form of Latin <i>Clementia</i>, a derivative of <i>Clemens</i> (  see  Clement  ) or an abstract noun meaning ‘mercy’. It was fairly popular in Britain from the late medieval period until the 17th century, but has since been used less often."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Clemence Rethel was born in 1214, in Reims, Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, France, her father, Gauthier \"le Dévôt\" de Réthel comte de Rethel, was 114 and her mother, Beatrix of Namur, was 104. She married Hugh de Pierrepont about 1150, in Hurstpierpoint, Sussex, England. They were the parents of at least 6 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1191, in England."},"et":{"Abt. 1133–1191":"1214–1191","1131–1185":"1131–1185","1140–1198":"1140–1198","1214–1191":"1214–1191","1129–1188":"1129–1188","1154–Male":"1154–Surnud","1156–Male":"11